            "status": -1,
            "desc": "September 3, 2025 The Royal Society has awarded Michael Thackeray, an emeritus materials chemist and Distinguished Fellow at Argonne, its Leverhulme Medal in recognition of his career in the discovery, design and development of advanced materials for lithium-ion batteries. Argonne National Laboratory. (Image by Argonne National Laboratory.) Michael Thackeray, an emeritus materials chemist and Distinguished Fellow at the U.S. Department of Energy’s (DOE) Argonne National Laboratory, has been awarded the Leverhulme Medal from the Royal Society. Thackeray is being honored for a career devoted to the discovery, design and development of advanced materials for lithium-ion batteries, which have become a cornerstone of modern energy storage systems. Founded in London in 1660, the Royal Society is the oldest scientific academy in continuous existence. Its Leverhulme Medal has been awarded triennially since 1960 to citizens and long-term residents of the Commonwealth and Ireland for outstanding contributions in the fields of chemical engineering and applied chemistry. The medal is supported by the Leverhulme Trust, established under the will of Victorian entrepreneur, William Lever. In a career spanning more than half a century, Thackeray has made groundbreaking contributions to the field of battery materials research. Educated at the University of Cape Town, where he earned a doctorate in chemistry, Thackeray began his research career in 1973 at the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research in South Africa. There, he and Johan Coetzer initiated studies of high-temperature sodium and lithium batteries in response to the Middle East oil crisis dominating global energy concerns at that time. “I hope that this recognition inspires the next generation of researchers to continue pushing the boundaries of science and technology.” — Michael Thackeray, emeritus materials chemist and Argonne Distinguished Fellow In the early 1980s, while at the University of Oxford, Thackeray collaborated with future Nobel laureate John Goodenough, who had recently discovered LiCoO2 (lithium cobalt oxide) as a potential cathode for a room-temperature lithium cell that, a decade later, would become the material of choice for the first commercial lithium-ion battery. Together with Bill David and Peter Bruce, they discovered the utility of lithium-manganese-oxide spinel cathodes, such as LiMn2O4, which laid the foundation for the development of the second lithium-ion battery system, used in applications including the first generation of the Nissan Leaf electric vehicle. In 1994, Thackeray was invited to join the Battery Department at Argonne National Laboratory. There, along with Argonne Distinguished Fellow Chris Johnson and other colleagues, he coinvented the lithium-nickel-manganese-cobalt-oxide (NMC) cathode technology, which is now widely used in lithium-ion batteries to power a myriad of devices. Michael Thackery. (Image by Michael Thackery.) During his career, Thackeray has served as director of the Center for Electrical Energy Storage, a DOE Energy Frontier Research Center, and as deputy director of its successor, the Center for Electrochemical Energy Science. He also spent more than 25 years in leadership roles at the International Battery Association, including serving as president, chairman and a board member. Thackeray is a Member of the National Academy of Engineering, and a Fellow of the Royal Society, the National Academy of Inventors, the Electrochemical Society and the Stellenbosch Institute for Advanced Study in South Africa. “Receiving the Leverhulme Medal from the Royal Society is not just a recognition of my work but also a testament to the collaborative efforts of the many scientists and engineers I’ve had the privilege to work with over the years,” Thackeray said. “I hope that this recognition inspires the next generation of researchers to continue pushing the boundaries of science and technology.” Argonne National Laboratory seeks solutions to pressing national problems in science and technology by conducting leading-edge basic and applied research in virtually every scientific discipline. Argonne is managed by UChicago Argonne, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy’s Office of Science. The U.S. Department of Energy’s Office of Science is the single largest supporter of basic research in the physical sciences in the United States and is working to address some of the most pressing challenges of our time. For more information, visit https://energy.gov/science. Tags: Chemistry, Energy Technology and Storage, Batteries and Fuel Cells, Materials Science and Engineering, About Argonne, Awards and Recognition, We Are Argonne 原文链接 https://www.anl.gov/article/michael-thackeray-awarded-leverhulme-medal-from-the-royal-society",
